{{Quote|Before Lucasfilm or American Zoetrope, or many other independent film enterprises in the San Francisco Bay Area, there was director John Korty. An inspiration to George Lucas among others, and longtime collaborator with Lucasfilm, our company mourns the recent passing of this intrepid and independent filmmaker.|A statement from Lucasfilm following John Korty's death|<ref name="Lucasfilm obituary">{{Lucasfilm|url=news/lucasfilm-remembers-john-korty|text=Lucasfilm Remembers John Korty
|archivedate=archivedate=20220630072822}}</ref>}}
'''John Korty''' ([[June 22]], [[1930s|1936]]<ref name="SWYT 25-06-2020" />&mdash;[[March 9]], [[2022]]<ref name="Death Cite" />) was the director of ''[[Caravan of Courage: An Ewok Adventure]]'' ([[1984]]). In [[1978]], Korty won the [[Wikipedia:Academy Award for Documentary Feature|Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]] and the [[Wikipedia:Primetime Emmy Award|Primetime Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Individual Achievement – Informational Programming for his work on [[Wikipedia:Who Are the DeBolts? And Where Did They Get Nineteen Kids?|''Who Are the DeBolts? And Where Did They Get Nineteen Kids?'']] For [[Lucasfilm]], he also directed the animated feature [[Wikipedia:Twice Upon a Time (1983 film)|''Twice Upon a Time'']].<ref name="Lucasfilm obituary" />

